Shortest path planning¶

example from motion planning course offered by Univ of Toronto

A map of Berkley, California is given

  • Implement Dijkstra's search algorithm on a road network graph.
  • Implement the A* search algorithm using a Euclidean heuristic on a road network graph.

OSMNX library is used to generate Python graphs from Open Street Map (OSM) data.

import networkx as nx
import numpy as np
from sklearn.neighbors import KDTree

We are going to local path planning in Berkeley, California, between the two nodes given below. After running the code up to and including the box below, you should see the output of the shortest path between the two points.

In [ ]:
origin =list(nodes)[0]
destination = list(nodes)[3000]
print("origin is = ",origin,"destination is =",destination)
shortest_path = nx.shortest_path(map_graph, source=origin, target=destination, weight="length", method='dijkstra')
print("Shortest path is = ",shortest_path)
print(type(shortest_path))

# Problem adapted from Introduction to AI, U of Toronto
# https://github.com/booklover98/A-star-Pathfinding

oshawa = (43.945403, -78.892466)
G = ox.graph_from_point(oshawa, dist=2000)
fig,ax=ox.plot_graph(G, node_size=1, edge_color='orange', bgcolor='#000000', show=False)
start = ox.geocode('2000 Simcoe St N, Oshawa, Ontario')
end = ox.geocode('18 Niagara Dr, Oshawa, Ontario')
ax.scatter(start[1],start[0],marker="+",s=100,color="blue")
ax.scatter(end[1],end[0],marker="+",s=100,color="white")
print(G.nodes.data())


#Convert the graph into geopandas dataframe
# easy to query closest node etc
nodes, _ = ox.graph_to_gdfs(G)
print(type(nodes[['y','x']]))
print(nodes[['y','x']])

tree = KDTree(nodes[['y','x']], metric='euclidean')

start_idx = tree.query([start],return_distance=False)[0]
print("Nearest start node number = ",start_idx)
end_idx = tree.query([end],return_distance=False)[0]
print("Nearest end node number = ",end_idx)

closest_start_node = nodes.iloc[start_idx]
closest_end_node = nodes.iloc[end_idx]
print("closest start node info = " ,closest_start_node)
print("closest end node info = " ,closest_end_node)

#retrieve origin and destination node id
origin =closest_start_node.index.values[0] 
destination = closest_end_node.index.values[0] 
print("closest start node osmid = " ,origin)
print("closest end node osmid = ",destination )

shortest_path = nx.shortest_path(G, source=origin, target=destination, weight="length", method='dijkstra')
print("Shortest Path is = ",shortest_path)

tree = KDTree(nodes[['y','x']], metric='euclidean')

start_idx = tree.query([start],return_distance=False)[0]
print("Nearest start node number = ",start_idx)
end_idx = tree.query([end],return_distance=False)[0]
print("Nearest end node number = ",end_idx)

closest_start_node = nodes.iloc[start_idx]
closest_end_node = nodes.iloc[end_idx]
print("closest start node info = " ,closest_start_node)
print("closest end node info = " ,closest_end_node)

#retrieve origin and destination node id
origin =closest_start_node.index.values[0] 
destination = closest_end_node.index.values[0] 
print("closest start node osmid = " ,origin)
print("closest end node osmid = ",destination )

#shortest path between source and destination
shortest_path = nx.shortest_path(G, source=origin, target=destination, weight="length", method='dijkstra')
print("Shortest Path is = ",shortest_path)
